      "text": "**Problem:** The world seems massively complex. People would not be able to cope in situations that are too complex.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e32dfb15e110890f",
      "text": "**Therefore:** You could create simplified models of complex situations and build theoretical complexity if you externalize it - whether you can juggle four, five, seven, or nine things in your head at the same time: It is definitely too little.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9631639c177797ac",
      "text": "**Notes:** \n* We must understand the complexity before we make simplified models.\n* We must be able to move back and forth between the complex situation and the model of some aspects of the situation—in order to be sure the model is still serving our needs.\n* Rules of thumb are not models.\n* Unlike natural sciences, humanities and social scientists cannot externalize complexity in experimental systems or laboratories. It has been convincingly shown in science research that the possibilities of scientific thinking are limited above all by the possibilities of the technology used. Why should this be fundamentally different in the humanities and social sciences? (cf. Ahrens, Das Zettelkasten-Prinzip, p. 108)"
